WEBVTT

1
00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:57.800
It's getting cold.

2
00:04:01.900 --> 00:04:05.000
That is one fine frame.

3
00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:07.200
One fine frame that is.

4
00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:10.200
- How much...

5
00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:16.600
does a fine frame like that
cost. do you think?

6
00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:22.200
I never told you. but you sound a little
like Dr. Seuss when you're drunk.

7
00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:25.500
I know.
I'm serious.

8
00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:27.400
Serious. I am.

9
00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:32.100
I'd say it cost at least
a couple hundred.

10
00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:36.400
- I'm gonna read it for you.
- Do I really sound like Dr. Seuss?

11
00:04:36.500 --> 00:04:39.500
"In recognition of his
outstanding achievement...

12
00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:42.100
- " in the field of child psychology.
- Mm-hmm.

13
00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:46.900
his dedication to his work
and his continuing efforts to
improve the quality of life-- "

14
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.300
- Will you concentrate?

15
00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:53.500
"...his continuing efforts to
improve the quality of life...

16
00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:56.400
"for countless children
and their families.

17
00:04:56.400 --> 00:05:00.300
"the city of Philadelphia
proudly bestows upon its son...

18
00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:03.000
Dr. Malcolm Crowe--"
That's you--

19
00:05:03.100 --> 00:05:05.900
"...the Mayor's Citation
for professional excellence."

20
00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:10.500
They called you their son.

21
00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:13.200
Wow.

22
00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:15.600
We should hang it
in the bathroom.

23
00:05:18.600 --> 00:05:21.100
This is an important
night for us.

24
00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:26.600
Finally. someone is recognizing
the sacrifices you've made--

25
00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:31.000
that you have put everything
second. including me.

26
00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:34.100
for those families that
they're talking about.

27
00:05:37.800 --> 00:05:40.700
They're also saying that
my husband has a gift.

28
00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:44.000
You have a gift
that teaches children...

29
00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:46.600
- how to be strong in situations...

30
00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:49.400
where most adults
would piss on themselves.

31
00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:53.000
I believe
what they wrote is real.

32
00:05:57.100 --> 00:05:59.000
Thank you.

33
00:06:02.400 --> 00:06:05.000
- I would like some wine in a glass.
- Mm- hmm.

34
00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:07.000
I would not like it
in a mug.

35
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:11.500
- I would not like it in a jug.

36
00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:34.400
Look.

37
00:07:15.800 --> 00:07:18.300
Anna. don't move.
Don't make a sound.

38
00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:25.600
This is 47 Locus Street.

39
00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:29.200
You've broken a window
and entered a private residence.

40
00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:32.800
You don't know so many things.

41
00:07:32.900 --> 00:07:38.400
There are no needles or prescription
drugs of any kind in this house.

42
00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:49.000
Do you know why you're afraid
when you're alone?

43
00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:54.800
I do.
I do.

44
00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:57.000
What do you want?

45
00:07:57.100 --> 00:08:00.800
What he promised me!
I want what he promised me.

46
00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:03.100
- Oh. my God.
- Do I know you?

47
00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:06.700
Don't you know me. hero?

48
00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:08.800
Don't you even remember
your own patients?

49
00:08:13.100 --> 00:08:15.700
Downtown clinic.

50
00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:18.100
Single- parent family.

51
00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:21.300
Possible mood disorder.

52
00:08:23.500 --> 00:08:25.600
I was afraid!

53
00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:30.100
You told me I was having trouble
coping with my parents' divorce.

54
00:08:30.200 --> 00:08:32.900
You were wrong.
You were wrong.

55
00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:37.900
Now look at me!

56
00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:42.200
- I don't want to be afraid no more.
- Just give me a minute to think.

57
00:08:42.300 --> 00:08:44.400
I waited
ten years for you!

58
00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:46.300
I'm not giving you nothing!

59
00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:49.000
Ben Friedkin?

60
00:08:49.100 --> 00:08:53.200
Some people.
they call me "freak."

61
00:08:53.300 --> 00:08:55.400
Ryan Summer?

62
00:08:55.400 --> 00:08:58.400
I am. I am a freak.
Look at--

63
00:09:00.400 --> 00:09:02.400
Vincent.

64
00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:04.400
Vincent Gray.

65
00:09:06.600 --> 00:09:09.100
No. you don't.

66
00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:11.500
I do remember you.

67
00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:15.000
Quiet. very smart.

68
00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:17.000
Compassionate.

69
00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:21.000
Unusually compassionate.

70
00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:25.100
You forgot cursed.

71
00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:30.800
You failed me.

72
00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:32.600
You failed me!

73
00:09:36.200 --> 00:09:39.800
Vincent. I'm sorry if I wasn't--
if I didn't help you.

74
00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:42.600
But if you just let me try.

75
00:09:42.600 --> 00:09:44.800
if you just
give me a chance--

76
00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:55.100
Oh. God! Oh. God!

77
00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:58.000
- Did Vincent--
- Don't talk. Shh.

78
00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:25.400
It's okay. Cole.

79
00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:28.100
My name is Dr. Malcolm Crowe.

80
00:12:29.700 --> 00:12:33.400
We were supposed to meet today.
but I missed our appointment.

81
00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:35.300
I'm sorry.

82
00:12:43.600 --> 00:12:48.500
You know. in the olden days in Europe.
people used to hide out in churches.

83
00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:50.800
They would claim sanctuary.

84
00:12:55.700 --> 00:12:57.600
What were they hiding from?

85
00:13:01.100 --> 00:13:03.200
Bad people. mostly.

86
00:13:03.300 --> 00:13:07.600
People that wanted to
put them in jail. hurt them.

87
00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.600
I noticed your eyeglasses.
They don't have any lenses in them.

88
00:13:13.700 --> 00:13:15.800
They're my dad's.

89
00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:18.200
The lenses hurt my eyes.

90
00:13:19.800 --> 00:13:24.000
What were you talking about with your
soldiers when I came in? Day--

91
00:13:24.100 --> 00:13:26.800
Deprofundus clamo
adite domine.

92
00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:29.700
It's called " Latin."

93
00:13:34.100 --> 00:13:37.400
- All your soldiers speak Latin?
- No.

94
00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:39.300
Just one.

95
00:13:41.300 --> 00:13:43.600
Are you a good doctor?

96
00:13:44.600 --> 00:13:47.000
Well.

97
00:13:47.100 --> 00:13:48.900
I used to be.

98
00:13:50.200 --> 00:13:53.100
I won an award once
from the mayor.

99
00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:56.400
It had an expensive frame.

100
00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:11.900
I'm gonna see you again.
right?

101
00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.600
If that's okay with you.

102
00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:48.900
It's me.

103
00:16:31.300 --> 00:16:34.200
The turnpike westbound
slows at Valley Forge 24.

104
00:16:34.300 --> 00:16:37.500
On the Blue Ridge.
both directions generally slow
between number three and two--

105
00:16:41.400 --> 00:16:43.300
Hey. good morning.

106
00:16:50.500 --> 00:16:52.300
Cole.

107
00:16:55.600 --> 00:16:58.400
Cole!

108
00:16:58.400 --> 00:17:01.000
Hey. your Cocoa Puffs
are gettin' soggy.

109
00:17:03.300 --> 00:17:07.000
Let me see you.
Oh. honey. you got a spot.

110
00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:08.900
Head up.

111
00:17:13.900 --> 00:17:16.500
- Okay. here we go.

112
00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.100
Something you were
looking for. baby?

113
00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:36.700
Pop Tarts?

114
00:17:38.700 --> 00:17:40.600
They're right here.

115
00:17:41.900 --> 00:17:43.800
Oh.

116
00:17:49.700 --> 00:17:51.900
Well. what are you
thinking. Mama?

117
00:17:53.600 --> 00:17:56.700
Lots of things.

118
00:17:56.800 --> 00:17:58.900
Anything bad about me?

119
00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.800
Hey. look at my face.

120
00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:04.500
I was not thinking
something bad about you.

121
00:18:05.600 --> 00:18:07.500
Got it?

122
00:18:09.600 --> 00:18:11.500
Got it.

123
00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:14.800
- Here. head up.

124
00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:17.000
- That's Tommy.
- That's okay. You tuck it in.

125
00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.400
Cole. you want this?

126
00:18:48.500 --> 00:18:51.800
Hey. freak. how'd you like that
"arm around the shoulder" bit?

127
00:18:51.900 --> 00:18:54.400
I just made that up.
I went with it.

128
00:18:54.500 --> 00:18:57.000
It's what great actors do.
It's called "improv."

129
00:19:34.200 --> 00:19:36.400
Hey. baby.

130
00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:38.400
How was your day?

131
00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:42.500
Hmm?

132
00:19:45.500 --> 00:19:47.800
You know. you can tell me things
If you need to.

133
00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:56.000
Well. you know
what I did today?

134
00:19:56.100 --> 00:20:01.000
I. uh. I won the Pennsylvania Lottery
in the morning.

135
00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:02.900
I quit my jobs.

136
00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:07.700
and I ate a big picnic in the park
with lots of chocolate mousse pie.

137
00:20:07.800 --> 00:20:11.000
And then I swam
in the fountain all afternoon.

138
00:20:11.100 --> 00:20:13.000
What'd you do?

139
00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:21.500
I was picked first for
kick ball teams at recess.

140
00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:23.400
I hit a grand slam
to win the game.

141
00:20:23.500 --> 00:20:27.400
Everybody lifted me up
on their shoulders
and carried me around. cheering.

142
00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:35.000
Well. in that case. I am gonna
make you some triangle pancakes.

143
00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:37.900
You got an hour.

144
00:20:43.600 --> 00:20:45.600
Hi.

145
00:20:49.400 --> 00:20:51.700
Wanna sit?

146
00:20:56.100 --> 00:20:58.200
Don't feel like
talking today?

147
00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:03.700
Wanna play a game?

148
00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:07.500
It's a mind- reading game.

149
00:21:07.600 --> 00:21:09.500
Here's how it works.

150
00:21:09.600 --> 00:21:11.900
I read your mind.

151
00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:15.200
If what I say is right. you take
one step towards the chair.

152
00:21:15.200 --> 00:21:19.100
If what I say is wrong.
you take one step back...

153
00:21:19.200 --> 00:21:21.000
towards the doorway.

154
00:21:21.100 --> 00:21:24.500
If you reach the chair.
you sit down.

155
00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:28.300
If you reach the door.
you can go.

156
00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:31.600
Wanna play?

157
00:21:38.600 --> 00:21:40.400
Okay.

158
00:21:55.500 --> 00:21:58.800
When your mother and father
were first divorced.

159
00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:03.000
your mom went to see a doctor
like me. and he didn't help her.

160
00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.000
So you think I'm not going
to be able to help you.

161
00:22:21.400 --> 00:22:25.900
You're worried that she said
she told him things--

162
00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.200
things she couldn't tell
anyone else.

163
00:22:29.400 --> 00:22:31.300
Secrets.

164
00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:40.400
You have a secret.
but you don't want to tell me.

165
00:22:53.200 --> 00:22:57.100
Your dad gave you that watch
as a present just before he went away.

166
00:23:07.500 --> 00:23:09.800
He forgot it in a drawer.

167
00:23:09.900 --> 00:23:11.800
Doesn't work.

168
00:23:23.300 --> 00:23:26.600
You keep pretty quiet
in school. but...

169
00:23:26.600 --> 00:23:31.300
you're a good student. you've never
really been in any serious trouble.

170
00:23:38.300 --> 00:23:40.200
We were supposed
to draw a picture.

171
00:23:40.200 --> 00:23:42.300
Anything we wanted.

172
00:23:45.100 --> 00:23:48.000
I drew a man.

173
00:23:48.100 --> 00:23:50.900
He got hurt in the neck by
another man with a screwdriver.

174
00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:57.000
You saw that on TV. Cole?

175
00:24:00.400 --> 00:24:02.700
Everyone got upset.

176
00:24:03.800 --> 00:24:06.400
They had a meeting.

177
00:24:06.500 --> 00:24:08.400
Mom started crying.

178
00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:10.800
I don't draw
like that anymore.

179
00:24:12.900 --> 00:24:14.900
How do you draw now?

180
00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:20.300
I draw... people smiling.

181
00:24:20.400 --> 00:24:22.300
dogs running.

182
00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:25.500
rainbows.

183
00:24:26.700 --> 00:24:29.600
They don't have meetings
about rainbows.

184
00:24:30.700 --> 00:24:33.800
No. I guess they don't.

185
00:24:42.400 --> 00:24:44.800
What am I thinking now?

186
00:24:44.900 --> 00:24:48.300
I don't know
what you're thinking now.

187
00:24:54.400 --> 00:24:56.200
I was thinking...

188
00:24:56.200 --> 00:24:58.100
you're nice.

189
00:25:00.500 --> 00:25:02.400
but you can't help me.

190
00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:21.800
I thought you meant the other Italian
restaurant I asked you to marry me in.

191
00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:30.500
I'm so sorry. Anna.

192
00:25:31.900 --> 00:25:34.400
I just can't seem
to keep track of time.

193
00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:39.900
And I didn't have
a very good session today.

194
00:25:44.100 --> 00:25:46.800
They're both so similar.

195
00:25:46.900 --> 00:25:51.100
The same mannerisms. same expressions.
same things hanging over their head.

196
00:25:54.400 --> 00:25:56.800
I think it might be
some kind of abuse.

197
00:25:57.800 --> 00:26:01.100
Cole has...
scratches on his arm.

198
00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:03.700
I think they might be
fingernail cuts.

199
00:26:03.800 --> 00:26:06.000
Defensive cuts. maybe.
I don't know.

200
00:26:07.500 --> 00:26:10.800
Maybe a teacher or a neighbor.

201
00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:15.400
I don't think it's the mother.
I've seen her with him.
and it doesn't seem to fit.

202
00:26:18.700 --> 00:26:20.600
Or I could just be wrong.

203
00:26:20.600 --> 00:26:23.600
Maybe he's just a kid
who likes to climb trees a lot.

204
00:26:31.600 --> 00:26:33.800
Anna.

205
00:26:35.100 --> 00:26:38.000
I know that I've been
a little distant. all right?

206
00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:41.100
I know that it makes you mad.
I just...

207
00:26:41.200 --> 00:26:45.000
feel like I'm being given
a second chance. and
I don't want it to slip away.

208
00:26:46.100 --> 00:26:48.200
- Anna.

209
00:26:50.100 --> 00:26:52.000
Happy anniversary.

210
00:27:01.300 --> 00:27:03.200
Stop looking at me.

211
00:27:03.200 --> 00:27:06.000
I don't like when people
look at me like that.

212
00:27:06.100 --> 00:27:08.600
- Okay.

213
00:27:08.600 --> 00:27:12.400
I walk this way to school
with Tommy Tammisimo.

214
00:27:12.500 --> 00:27:14.400
Is he your best buddy?

215
00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:16.300
He hates me.

216
00:27:16.400 --> 00:27:18.700
Do you hate him?

217
00:27:18.800 --> 00:27:20.800
No.

218
00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:24.300
Did your mom
set that up?

219
00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:26.200
Yes.

220
00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.400
Did you ever talk to your mom
about how things are with Tommy?

221
00:27:30.500 --> 00:27:33.500
- I don't tell her things.
- Why not?

222
00:27:33.600 --> 00:27:36.100
'Cause she doesn't look at me like
everybody else. and I don't want her to.

223
00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:38.800
- I don't want her to know.
- Know what?

224
00:27:38.900 --> 00:27:41.200
That I'm a freak.

225
00:27:41.300 --> 00:27:43.300
Hey.

226
00:27:43.400 --> 00:27:47.200
You are not a freak.
Okay?

227
00:27:47.300 --> 00:27:51.900
Don't you believe anybody that tries to
convince you of that. That's bullshit.

228
00:27:51.900 --> 00:27:54.200
You don't have to go through
your life believing that.

229
00:27:55.900 --> 00:27:57.700
Okay?

230
00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:01.900
Come on.

231
00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:09.000
- You said the "S" word.
- Yeah. I know.

232
00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:10.900
Sorry.

233
00:29:15.200 --> 00:29:17.600
So your dad lives
in Pittsburgh with a lady...

234
00:29:17.600 --> 00:29:19.800
that works in a tollbooth?

235
00:29:21.900 --> 00:29:25.100
I wonder if she has to pee
when she's working.

236
00:29:25.100 --> 00:29:27.100
Think she just holds it?

237
00:29:27.200 --> 00:29:30.400
I don't know. I was just
thinking about that myself.

238
00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:34.000
You asked a lot of questions
about Dad today.

239
00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:36.200
How come?

240
00:29:36.300 --> 00:29:39.900
Well. sometimes we do things
to draw attention.

241
00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:44.900
to express our feelings
about certain issues--

242
00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:48.200
divorce. whatever.

243
00:29:48.300 --> 00:29:51.800
For example. a person might
leave something on the desk
for someone else to find.

244
00:29:56.200 --> 00:29:58.600
Do you know what free
association writing is. Cole?

245
00:29:59.900 --> 00:30:01.800
No.

246
00:30:01.900 --> 00:30:06.000
Free association writing
is when you take a pencil in your hand.

247
00:30:06.100 --> 00:30:11.200
and you put the pencil to apiece
of paper and you start writing.

248
00:30:11.300 --> 00:30:13.900
And you don't look
at what you're writing or
think about what you're writing.

249
00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:17.200
You just keep
Your hand moving.

250
00:30:17.300 --> 00:30:21.100
And after a while. if you keep
Your hand moving long enough.

251
00:30:21.200 --> 00:30:24.400
words and thoughts start coming out that
you didn't even know you had in you.

252
00:30:24.600 --> 00:30:29.700
It could be something
you heard somewhere else.

253
00:30:29.800 --> 00:30:33.000
or feelings you had
deep inside of you.

254
00:30:36.500 --> 00:30:39.000
Have you ever done any
free association writing. Cole?

255
00:30:42.600 --> 00:30:44.500
Yes.

256
00:30:44.500 --> 00:30:46.500
What did you write?

257
00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:49.800
Upset words.

258
00:30:51.600 --> 00:30:54.800
Did you ever write any upset words
before your father left?

259
00:30:56.200 --> 00:30:58.000
